Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Marks: 60

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

E-news Express, an online news portal, aims to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. The design team of the company has researched and created a new landing page that has a new outline & more relevant content shown compared to the old page. In order to test the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers, the Data Science team conducted an experiment by randomly selecting 100 users and dividing them equally into two groups.

The objective is to explore the data and perform a statistical analysis (at a significance level of 5%) to determine the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers for the news portal by answering the following questions:

  • Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?
  • Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?
  • Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?
  • Is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

$H_0$: Mean time users spend on new and old landing page is the same\ $H_a$: Mean time users spend on new landing page is more than old landing page

or

$H_0:\mu_1=\mu_2$\ $H_a:\mu_1>\mu_2$

where $\mu_1$ is the mean time users spend on new landing page and $\mu_2$ is the mean time users spend on old landing page

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

This is a case of two independent sample t-test for equality of means with unknown standard deviation, and we shall use ttest_ind(), since the data is divided into two equal groups. The existing landing page is served to the first group(control group) and the new landing page is served to the treatment group, without any overlap of users between the two groups. The following assumptions are full-filled:

1) Data is continous - Time spent on landing pages are continous.
2) Normally distributed populations - Looking at the histogram, it can be interpreted that the distribution of the two samples are normal, also the sample size is greater than 30.
3) Independent Populations - As we are taking random samples for two different groups, the two samples are from two independent populations.
4) Unequal population standard deviations - As the sample standard deviations are different, the population standard deviations may assumed to be different.
5) Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample a simple random sample.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

Using a statistical significance level of 5%

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [35]:
#Computing the mean time of and sample standard deviations of users spent on the page
print('The mean time spent for control group is ' + str(round(df[df['group']=='control'].time_spent_on_the_page.mean(),1)) +' mins')
print('The mean time spent for treatment group is ' + str(round( df[df['group']=='treatment'].time_spent_on_the_page.mean(), 1))+' mins')
print('The standard deviation of time spent for control group is ' + str(round(df[df['group']=='control'].time_spent_on_the_page.std(),2)) +' mins')
print('The standard deviation of time spent for treatment group is ' + str(round(df[df['group']=='treatment'].time_spent_on_the_page.std(), 2))+' mins')

The mean time spent for control group is 4.5 mins
The mean time spent for treatment group is 6.2 mins
The standard deviation of time spent for control group is 2.58 mins
The standard deviation of time spent for treatment group is 1.82 mins

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [36]:
#importing ttest_ind() from scipy.stats

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind

#computing the test-statistic and p-value of ttest_ind()

test_statistic,p_value = ttest_ind(df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'],df_old['time_spent_on_the_page'],equal_var =False,alternative='greater')

print('The p-value is',p_value)

The p-value is 0.0001392381225166549

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

  • Since p_value of 0.00013 is less than the level of significance of 0.05 and hence we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

  • Based on the above p_value, we have enough evidence to conclude that the mean time users spend on new landing page is more than old landing page.

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

Using proportions z-test to test if conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page, with the following hypothesis:

$H_0$: Proportion of users who visit new landing page (p1) = Proportion of users who visit old landing page (p2)\ $H_a$: Proportion of users who visit new landing page (p2) > Proportion of users who visit old landing page (p2)

or

$H_0:p_1 = p_2$ $H_a:p_1 > p_2$

The assumptions of proportions z-test are also satisified as noted below:

  • Binomally distributed population - Yes, a user is either converted or not converted.
  • Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a random sample.
  • Can the binomial distribution approximated to normal distribution - Yes. For binary data, Central Limit Theorem works slower than usual. Have further checked the standard if np and n(1-p) are greater than or equal to 10. Here, n and p refer to the sample size and sample proportion respectively.

    $np_1 = 50\cdot \frac{33}{50} =33 \geq 10\\ n(1-p_1) = 50 \cdot \frac{50-33}{50} =17 \geq 10 \\ np_2 = 50\cdot \frac{21}{50} =21 \geq 10\\ n(1-p_2) = 50 \cdot \frac{50-21}{50} =29 \geq 10 $

In [42]:
#importing proportions_ztest from statsmodels.stats
from statsmodels.stats.proportion import proportions_ztest

#computing the test-statistic and p-value of proportions_ztest()

test_statistic,p_value = proportions_ztest(count=[33,21], nobs=[50,50],value =0, alternative='larger')

print('The p-value is',p_value)

The p-value is 0.008026308204056278

Since the p_value of 0.008 is less than the level of siginificance 0.05, we reject the null hypothesis, and can say that we have enough evidence to conclude that the conversion rate of new landing page is greater than the conversion rate of the old landing page.

3. Is the conversion and preferred language are independent or related?¶

Since both the concerned variables i.e. language preferred and converted are categorical in nature, we can use a contingency table and a stacked bar graph to visually inspect the data. Further to test the dependence between two categorical variables, a Chi-square test for independence can be used.

The following assumptions of chi-square test are satisfied:

  • Variables are categorical in nature as per the data set
  • Expected value of the number of sample observations in each level of the variable is at least 5 - Yes, the number of observations in each level is greater than 5.
  • Random sampling from the population - Yes, we are informed that the collected sample is a random sample.
In [43]:
#Using pd.crosstab to create a contingency table

Formulating Null and Alternate Hypothesis

$H_0$: conversion and preferred language are independent\ $H_a$: conversion and preferred language are dependent

Setting the level of significance (alpha) as 0.05

In [45]:
from scipy.stats import chi2_contingency

chi,p_value,dof,expected = chi2_contingency(contingency_table)
print('The test-statistic value is:', chi)
print('The p_value is:', p_value)
print('The degrees of freedom are:', dof)
print('The expected frequencies are:', expected)

The test-statistic value is: 3.0930306905370837
The p_value is: 0.21298887487543447
The degrees of freedom are: 2
The expected frequencies are: [[14.72 15.64 15.64]
 [17.28 18.36 18.36]]

Based on the p_value of 0.212 above which is higher than the level of significance 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. We do not have enough evidence to conclude that conversion and preferred language are dependent on each other.

4. Is the time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

In [46]:
#plotting a boxplot of different language users and time spent on the new page

sns.boxplot(x=df_new['language_preferred'],y=df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'])
Out[46]:
<AxesSubplot:xlabel='language_preferred', ylabel='time_spent_on_the_page'>

  • Based on the plot above, the median time spent on the new landing page is highest for English preferred users followed by spanish and then French.

  • There are outliers in terms of time spent for Spanish and French users with as low as less than ~1 minute spent by Spanish preferred users, and as high as more than 10 hours spent by French preferred users.

In order to test if the mean time of different language users are the same on the new page, ANOVA test can be used.

Consider $\mu_1,\mu_2 and \mu_3$ as the mean time of English, French and Spanish language users spent on the new landing page, and hence the hypothesis is formulated as follows:

$H_0$: Mean time spent on the new page is the same for all three language users\ $H_a$: At least one of the mean time of the three language users is different

or

$H_0: \mu_1=\mu_2=\mu_3$\ $H_a: \mu_1\neq\mu_2$ or $\mu_2\neq\mu_3$ or $\mu_1\neq\mu_3$

Considering the level of significance at 5%

The following assumptions of ANOVA Test are also tested below:

For testing assumption of normality: Shapiro-Wilks test is applied to the response variable.
For testing assumption of equality of variances: Levene's test applied to the response variable.

Shapiro-Wilk’s test:¶

Formulating null and alternate hypothesis for Shapiro-Wilk's test -

$H_0$: Time spent on the new landing page follows a normal distribution\ $H_a$: Time spent on thew new landing page does not follow a normal distribution

In [47]:
#importing Shapiro from scipy.stats
from scipy.stats import shapiro

#performing the test to find p-value
test_statistic,p_value =shapiro(df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'])

print('The p_value of Shapiro-Wilk test is:',p_value)

The p_value of Shapiro-Wilk test is: 0.8040016293525696

Based on the p_value of 0.804 which is greater than the level of significance of 0.05, we fail to reject the null, and conclude that the time spent on the new landing page follows a normal distribution.

Levene's Test:¶

Formulating null and alternate hypothesis for Levene's test -

$H_0$: Variances of time spent by all different language users are equal\ $H_a$: Atleast one variance of the time spent by different language users are different

In [48]:
#importing levene from scipy.stats
from scipy.stats import levene

#performing the test to find p-value
test_statistic, p_value = levene( df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred']=="English"], 
                                   df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred']=="French"], 
                                   df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred']=="Spanish"])

print('The p-value of levene test is', p_value)

The p-value of levene test is 0.46711357711340173

Based on the p_value of levene's test of 0.467 which is greater than the level of significance of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis and it can be concluded that the variances of time spent by all different language users are equal.

Based on the test of assumptions of ANOVA Test, the following assumptions are satisfied -

  • The populations are normally distributed - Yes, the normality assumption is verified using the Shapiro-Wilks test.
  • Population variances are equal - Yes, the homogeneity of variance assumption is verified using the Levene's test.
  • Samples are independent simple random samples - Yes, we are informed that collected sample is a random sample.

Performing ANOVA test:¶

In [49]:
#importing f_oneway from scipy.stats
from scipy.stats import f_oneway

#performing the test to find p-value
test_statistic, p_value = f_oneway( df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred']=="English"], 
                                   df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred']=="French"], 
                                   df_new['time_spent_on_the_page'][df_new['language_preferred']=="Spanish"])

print('The p-value of f_oneway test is', p_value)

The p-value of f_oneway test is 0.43204138694325955

Based on the p_value of ANOVA test of 0.432 which is greater than the level of significant of 0.05, we fail to reject the null hypothesis. We do not have enough statistical evidence to conclude that the mean time spent by at least one of the English, French or Spanish language users is different.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

Conclusions:¶

  • From the above analysis, it can be concluded that E-news Express has been able to attract new subscribers/convert users basis the new landing page, and that the creation of this page proves to be effective for their business.
  • There is enough statistical evidence to conclude that the mean time users spend on new landing page is more than old landing page.
  • There is enough statistical evidence to conclude that the conversion rate of new landing page is greater than the conversion rate of the old landing page.
  • Although conversion rate and language preferred are not dependent on each other, still the new landing page has significantly helped E-news Express to convert the French users which were higher in number for non-conversion on the old landing page.
  • Conversion rate for the new landing page is higher for French (70%) and Spanish (64%) Language users followed by English language users (62%).
  • Irrespective of the group, converted users spend an average time of 6.6 mins on the two landing pages.
  • Overall, the average time spent by the treatment group has also improved and is much higher on the new landing page (6.2 mins).

Recomendations:¶

  • E-news Express can further gather data on the number of clicks, user location, news topics referred, news preferrences by users who spend more than 6 mins on an average on their landing page, since the sample data suggests that on an average all converted users spend about ~6.6 mins on the landing pages.
  • Conversion rate for the new landing page is lowest for English language users (62%), E-news Express data science team could analyse why this is the case and can futher collect more information about the English language preferred users to improve their conversion rate.
